   1 r'''Parse strings using a specification based on the Python format() syntax.
   2 
   3    ``parse()`` is the opposite of ``format()``
   4 
   5 The module is set up to only export ``parse()``, ``search()``, ``findall()``,
   6 and ``with_pattern()`` when ``import \*`` is used:
   7 
   8 >>> from parse import *
   9 
  10 From there it's a simple thing to parse a string:
  11 
  12 >>> parse("It's {}, I love it!", "It's spam, I love it!")
  13 <Result ('spam',) {}>
  14 >>> _[0]
  15 'spam'
  16 
  17 Or to search a string for some pattern:
  18 
  19 >>> search('Age: {:d}\n', 'Name: Rufus\nAge: 42\nColor: red\n')
  20 <Result (42,) {}>
  21 
  22 Or find all the occurrences of some pattern in a string:
  23 
  24 >>> ''.join(r[0] for r in findall(">{}<", "<p>the <b>bold</b> text</p>"))
  25 'the bold text'
  26 
  27 If you're going to use the same pattern to match lots of strings you can
  28 compile it once:
  29 
  30 >>> from parse import compile
  31 >>> p = compile("It's {}, I love it!")
  32 >>> print(p)
  33 <Parser "It's {}, I love it!">
  34 >>> p.parse("It's spam, I love it!")
  35 <Result ('spam',) {}>
  36 
  37 ("compile" is not exported for ``import *`` usage as it would override the
  38 built-in ``compile()`` function)
  39 
  40 The default behaviour is to match strings case insensitively. You may match with
  41 case by specifying `case_sensitive=True`:
  42 
  43 >>> parse('SPAM', 'spam', case_sensitive=True) is None
  44 True
  45 
  46 
  47 Format Syntax
  48 -------------
  49 
  50 A basic version of the `Format String Syntax`_ is supported with anonymous
  51 (fixed-position), named and formatted fields::
  52 
  53    {[field name]:[format spec]}
  54 
  55 Field names must be a valid Python identifiers, including dotted names;
  56 element indexes imply dictionaries (see below for example).
  57 
  58 Numbered fields are also not supported: the result of parsing will include
  59 the parsed fields in the order they are parsed.
  60 
  61 The conversion of fields to types other than strings is done based on the
  62 type in the format specification, which mirrors the ``format()`` behaviour.
  63 There are no "!" field conversions like ``format()`` has.
  64 
  65 Some simple parse() format string examples:
  66 
  67 >>> parse("Bring me a {}", "Bring me a shrubbery")
  68 <Result ('shrubbery',) {}>
  69 >>> r = parse("The {} who say {}", "The knights who say Ni!")
  70 >>> print(r)
  71 <Result ('knights', 'Ni!') {}>
  72 >>> print(r.fixed)
  73 ('knights', 'Ni!')
  74 >>> r = parse("Bring out the holy {item}", "Bring out the holy hand grenade")
  75 >>> print(r)
  76 <Result () {'item': 'hand grenade'}>
  77 >>> print(r.named)
  78 {'item': 'hand grenade'}
  79 >>> print(r['item'])
  80 hand grenade
  81 >>> 'item' in r
  82 True
  83 
  84 Note that `in` only works if you have named fields. Dotted names and indexes
  85 are possible though the application must make additional sense of the result:
  86 
  87 >>> r = parse("Mmm, {food.type}, I love it!", "Mmm, spam, I love it!")
  88 >>> print(r)
  89 <Result () {'food.type': 'spam'}>
  90 >>> print(r.named)
  91 {'food.type': 'spam'}
  92 >>> print(r['food.type'])
  93 spam
  94 >>> r = parse("My quest is {quest[name]}", "My quest is to seek the holy grail!")
  95 >>> print(r)
  96 <Result () {'quest': {'name': 'to seek the holy grail!'}}>
  97 >>> print(r['quest'])
  98 {'name': 'to seek the holy grail!'}
  99 >>> print(r['quest']['name'])
 100 to seek the holy grail!
 101 
 102 If the text you're matching has braces in it you can match those by including
 103 a double-brace ``{{`` or ``}}`` in your format string, just like format() does.
 104 
 105 
 106 Format Specification
 107 --------------------
 108 
 109 Most often a straight format-less ``{}`` will suffice where a more complex
 110 format specification might have been used.
 111 
 112 Most of `format()`'s `Format Specification Mini-Language`_ is supported:
 113 
 114    [[fill]align][0][width][.precision][type]
 115 
 116 The differences between `parse()` and `format()` are:
 117 
 118 - The align operators will cause spaces (or specified fill character) to be
 119   stripped from the parsed value. The width is not enforced; it just indicates
 120   there may be whitespace or "0"s to strip.
 121 - Numeric parsing will automatically handle a "0b", "0o" or "0x" prefix.
 122   That is, the "#" format character is handled automatically by d, b, o
 123   and x formats. For "d" any will be accepted, but for the others the correct
 124   prefix must be present if at all.
 125 - Numeric sign is handled automatically.
 126 - The thousands separator is handled automatically if the "n" type is used.
 127 - The types supported are a slightly different mix to the format() types.  Some
 128   format() types come directly over: "d", "n", "%", "f", "e", "b", "o" and "x".
 129   In addition some regular expression character group types "D", "w", "W", "s"
 130   and "S" are also available.
 131 - The "e" and "g" types are case-insensitive so there is not need for
 132   the "E" or "G" types. The "e" type handles Fortran formatted numbers (no
 133   leading 0 before the decimal point).
 134 
 135 ===== =========================================== ========
 136 Type  Characters Matched                          Output
 137 ===== =========================================== ========
 138 l     Letters (ASCII)                             str
 139 w     Letters, numbers and underscore             str
 140 W     Not letters, numbers and underscore         str
 141 s     Whitespace                                  str
 142 S     Non-whitespace                              str
 143 d     Digits (effectively integer numbers)        int
 144 D     Non-digit                                   str
 145 n     Numbers with thousands separators (, or .)  int
 146 %     Percentage (converted to value/100.0)       float
 147 f     Fixed-point numbers                         float
 148 F     Decimal numbers                             Decimal
 149 e     Floating-point numbers with exponent        float
 150       e.g. 1.1e-10, NAN (all case insensitive)
 151 g     General number format (either d, f or e)    float
 152 b     Binary numbers                              int
 153 o     Octal numbers                               int
 154 x     Hexadecimal numbers (lower and upper case)  int
 155 ti    ISO 8601 format date/time                   datetime
 156       e.g. 1972-01-20T10:21:36Z ("T" and "Z"
 157       optional)
 158 te    RFC2822 e-mail format date/time             datetime
 159       e.g. Mon, 20 Jan 1972 10:21:36 +1000
 160 tg    Global (day/month) format date/time         datetime
 161       e.g. 20/1/1972 10:21:36 AM +1:00
 162 ta    US (month/day) format date/time             datetime
 163       e.g. 1/20/1972 10:21:36 PM +10:30
 164 tc    ctime() format date/time                    datetime
 165       e.g. Sun Sep 16 01:03:52 1973
 166 th    HTTP log format date/time                   datetime
 167       e.g. 21/Nov/2011:00:07:11 +0000
 168 ts    Linux system log format date/time           datetime
 169       e.g. Nov  9 03:37:44
 170 tt    Time                                        time
 171       e.g. 10:21:36 PM -5:30
 172 ===== =========================================== ========
 173 
 174 Some examples of typed parsing with ``None`` returned if the typing
 175 does not match:
 176 
 177 >>> parse('Our {:d} {:w} are...', 'Our 3 weapons are...')
 178 <Result (3, 'weapons') {}>
 179 >>> parse('Our {:d} {:w} are...', 'Our three weapons are...')
 180 >>> parse('Meet at {:tg}', 'Meet at 1/2/2011 11:00 PM')
 181 <Result (datetime.datetime(2011, 2, 1, 23, 0),) {}>
 182 
 183 And messing about with alignment:
 184 
 185 >>> parse('with {:>} herring', 'with     a herring')
 186 <Result ('a',) {}>
 187 >>> parse('spam {:^} spam', 'spam    lovely     spam')
 188 <Result ('lovely',) {}>
 189 
 190 Note that the "center" alignment does not test to make sure the value is
 191 centered - it just strips leading and trailing whitespace.
 192 
 193 Width and precision may be used to restrict the size of matched text
 194 from the input. Width specifies a minimum size and precision specifies
 195 a maximum. For example:
 196 
 197 >>> parse('{:.2}{:.2}', 'look')           # specifying precision
 198 <Result ('lo', 'ok') {}>
 199 >>> parse('{:4}{:4}', 'look at that')     # specifying width
 200 <Result ('look', 'at that') {}>
 201 >>> parse('{:4}{:.4}', 'look at that')    # specifying both
 202 <Result ('look at ', 'that') {}>
 203 >>> parse('{:2d}{:2d}', '0440')           # parsing two contiguous numbers
 204 <Result (4, 40) {}>
 205 
 206 Some notes for the date and time types:
 207 
 208 - the presence of the time part is optional (including ISO 8601, starting
 209   at the "T"). A full datetime object will always be returned; the time
 210   will be set to 00:00:00. You may also specify a time without seconds.
 211 - when a seconds amount is present in the input fractions will be parsed
 212   to give microseconds.
 213 - except in ISO 8601 the day and month digits may be 0-padded.
 214 - the date separator for the tg and ta formats may be "-" or "/".
 215 - named months (abbreviations or full names) may be used in the ta and tg
 216   formats in place of numeric months.
 217 - as per RFC 2822 the e-mail format may omit the day (and comma), and the
 218   seconds but nothing else.
 219 - hours greater than 12 will be happily accepted.
 220 - the AM/PM are optional, and if PM is found then 12 hours will be added
 221   to the datetime object's hours amount - even if the hour is greater
 222   than 12 (for consistency.)
 223 - in ISO 8601 the "Z" (UTC) timezone part may be a numeric offset
 224 - timezones are specified as "+HH:MM" or "-HH:MM". The hour may be one or two
 225   digits (0-padded is OK.) Also, the ":" is optional.
 226 - the timezone is optional in all except the e-mail format (it defaults to
 227   UTC.)
 228 - named timezones are not handled yet.
 229 
 230 Note: attempting to match too many datetime fields in a single parse() will
 231 currently result in a resource allocation issue. A TooManyFields exception
 232 will be raised in this instance. The current limit is about 15. It is hoped
 233 that this limit will be removed one day.
 234 
 235 .. _`Format String Syntax`:
 236   http://docs.python.org/library/string.html#format-string-syntax
 237 .. _`Format Specification Mini-Language`:
 238   http://docs.python.org/library/string.html#format-specification-mini-language
 239

 241 Result and Match Objects
 242 ------------------------
 243 
 244 The result of a ``parse()`` and ``search()`` operation is either ``None`` (no match), a
 245 ``Result`` instance or a ``Match`` instance if ``evaluate_result`` is False.
 246 
 247 The ``Result`` instance has three attributes:
 248 
 249 fixed
 250    A tuple of the fixed-position, anonymous fields extracted from the input.
 251 named
 252    A dictionary of the named fields extracted from the input.
 253 spans
 254    A dictionary mapping the names and fixed position indices matched to a
 255    2-tuple slice range of where the match occurred in the input.
 256    The span does not include any stripped padding (alignment or width).
 257 
 258 The ``Match`` instance has one method:
 259 
 260 evaluate_result()
 261    Generates and returns a ``Result`` instance for this ``Match`` object.
 262 
 263 
 264 
 265 Custom Type Conversions
 266 -----------------------
 267 
 268 If you wish to have matched fields automatically converted to your own type you
 269 may pass in a dictionary of type conversion information to ``parse()`` and
 270 ``compile()``.
 271 
 272 The converter will be passed the field string matched. Whatever it returns
 273 will be substituted in the ``Result`` instance for that field.
 274 
 275 Your custom type conversions may override the builtin types if you supply one
 276 with the same identifier.
 277 
 278 >>> def shouty(string):
 279 ...    return string.upper()
 280 ...
 281 >>> parse('{:shouty} world', 'hello world', dict(shouty=shouty))
 282 <Result ('HELLO',) {}>
 283 
 284 If the type converter has the optional ``pattern`` attribute, it is used as
 285 regular expression for better pattern matching (instead of the default one).
 286 
 287 >>> def parse_number(text):
 288 ...    return int(text)
 289 >>> parse_number.pattern = r'\d+'
 290 >>> parse('Answer: {number:Number}', 'Answer: 42', dict(Number=parse_number))
 291 <Result () {'number': 42}>
 292 >>> _ = parse('Answer: {:Number}', 'Answer: Alice', dict(Number=parse_number))
 293 >>> assert _ is None, "MISMATCH"
 294 
 295 You can also use the ``with_pattern(pattern)`` decorator to add this
 296 information to a type converter function:
 297 
 298 >>> from parse import with_pattern
 299 >>> @with_pattern(r'\d+')
 300 ... def parse_number(text):
 301 ...    return int(text)
 302 >>> parse('Answer: {number:Number}', 'Answer: 42', dict(Number=parse_number))
 303 <Result () {'number': 42}>
 304 
 305 A more complete example of a custom type might be:
 306 
 307 >>> yesno_mapping = {
 308 ...     "yes":  True,   "no":    False,
 309 ...     "on":   True,   "off":   False,
 310 ...     "true": True,   "false": False,
 311 ... }
 312 >>> @with_pattern(r"|".join(yesno_mapping))
 313 ... def parse_yesno(text):
 314 ...     return yesno_mapping[text.lower()]
 315 
 316 
 317 If the type converter ``pattern`` uses regex-grouping (with parenthesis),
 318 you should indicate this by using the optional ``regex_group_count`` parameter
 319 in the ``with_pattern()`` decorator:
 320 
 321 >>> @with_pattern(r'((\d+))', regex_group_count=2)
 322 ... def parse_number2(text):
 323 ...    return int(text)
 324 >>> parse('Answer: {:Number2} {:Number2}', 'Answer: 42 43', dict(Number2=parse_number2))
 325 <Result (42, 43) {}>
 326 
 327 Otherwise, this may cause parsing problems with unnamed/fixed parameters.
 328 
 329 
 330 Potential Gotchas
 331 -----------------
 332 
 333 `parse()` will always match the shortest text necessary (from left to right)
 334 to fulfil the parse pattern, so for example:
 335 
 336 >>> pattern = '{dir1}/{dir2}'
 337 >>> data = 'root/parent/subdir'
 338 >>> sorted(parse(pattern, data).named.items())
 339 [('dir1', 'root'), ('dir2', 'parent/subdir')]
 340 
 341 So, even though `{'dir1': 'root/parent', 'dir2': 'subdir'}` would also fit
 342 the pattern, the actual match represents the shortest successful match for
 343 `dir1`.

 442 def with_pattern(pattern, regex_group_count=None):
 443     r"""Attach a regular expression pattern matcher to a custom type converter
 444     function.
 445 
 446     This annotates the type converter with the :attr:`pattern` attribute.
 447 
 448     EXAMPLE:
 449         >>> import parse
 450         >>> @parse.with_pattern(r"\d+")
 451         ... def parse_number(text):
 452         ...     return int(text)
 453 
 454     is equivalent to:
 455 
 456         >>> def parse_number(text):
 457         ...     return int(text)
 458         >>> parse_number.pattern = r"\d+"
 459 
 460     :param pattern: regular expression pattern (as text)
 461     :param regex_group_count: Indicates how many regex-groups are in pattern.
 462     :return: wrapped function
 463     """
 464     def decorator(func):
 465         func.pattern = pattern
 466         func.regex_group_count = regex_group_count
 467         return func
 468     return decorator

 471 def int_convert(base=None):
 472     '''Convert a string to an integer.
 473 
 474     The string may start with a sign.
 475 
 476     It may be of a base other than 2, 8, 10 or 16.
 477 
 478     If base isn't specified, it will be detected automatically based
 479     on a string format. When string starts with a base indicator, 0#nnnn, 
 480     it overrides the default base of 10.
 481 
 482     It may also have other non-numeric characters that we can ignore.
 483     '''
 484     CHARS = '0123456789abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz'
 485 
 486     def f(string, match, base=base):
 487         if string[0] == '-':
 488             sign = -1
 489             number_start = 1
 490         elif string[0] == '+':
 491             sign = 1
 492             number_start = 1
 493         else:
 494             sign = 1
 495             number_start = 0
 496 
 497         # If base wasn't specified, detect it automatically
 498         if base is None:
 499 
 500           # Assume decimal number, unless different base is detected
 501           base = 10
 502 
 503           # For number formats starting with 0b, 0o, 0x, use corresponding base ...
 504           if string[number_start] == '0' and len(string) - number_start > 2:
 505               if string[number_start+1] in 'bB':
 506                   base = 2
 507               elif string[number_start+1] in 'oO':
 508                   base = 8
 509               elif string[number_start+1] in 'xX':
 510                   base = 16
 511 
 512         chars = CHARS[:base]
 513         string = re.sub('[^%s]' % chars, '', string.lower())
 514         return sign * int(string, base)
 515     return f
 516 
 517 
 518 def percentage(string, match):
 519     return float(string[:-1]) / 100.

 522 class FixedTzOffset(tzinfo):
 523     """Fixed offset in minutes east from UTC.
 524     """
 525     ZERO = timedelta(0)
 526 
 527     def __init__(self, offset, name):
 528         self._offset = timedelta(minutes=offset)
 529         self._name = name
 530 
 531     def __repr__(self):
 532         return '<%s %s %s>' % (self.__class__.__name__, self._name,
 533             self._offset)
 534 
 535     def utcoffset(self, dt):
 536         return self._offset
 537 
 538     def tzname(self, dt):
 539         return self._name
 540 
 541     def dst(self, dt):
 542         return self.ZERO
 543 
 544     def __eq__(self, other):
 545         if not isinstance(other, FixedTzOffset):
 546             return False
 547         return self._name == other._name and self._offset == other._offset

 550 MONTHS_MAP = dict(
 551     Jan=1, January=1,
 552     Feb=2, February=2,
 553     Mar=3, March=3,
 554     Apr=4, April=4,
 555     May=5,
 556     Jun=6, June=6,
 557     Jul=7, July=7,
 558     Aug=8, August=8,
 559     Sep=9, September=9,
 560     Oct=10, October=10,
 561     Nov=11, November=11,
 562     Dec=12, December=12
 563 )
 564 DAYS_PAT = r'(Mon|Tue|Wed|Thu|Fri|Sat|Sun)'
 565 MONTHS_PAT = r'(Jan|Feb|Mar|Apr|May|Jun|Jul|Aug|Sep|Oct|Nov|Dec)'
 566 ALL_MONTHS_PAT = r'(%s)' % '|'.join(MONTHS_MAP)
 567 TIME_PAT = r'(\d{1,2}:\d{1,2}(:\d{1,2}(\.\d+)?)?)'
 568 AM_PAT = r'(\s+[AP]M)'
 569 TZ_PAT = r'(\s+[-+]\d\d?:?\d\d)'

 572 def date_convert(string, match, ymd=None, mdy=None, dmy=None,
 573         d_m_y=None, hms=None, am=None, tz=None, mm=None, dd=None):
 574     '''Convert the incoming string containing some date / time info into a
 575     datetime instance.
 576     '''
 577     groups = match.groups()
 578     time_only = False
 579     if mm and dd:
 580         y=datetime.today().year
 581         m=groups[mm]
 582         d=groups[dd]
 583     elif ymd is not None:
 584         y, m, d = re.split(r'[-/\s]', groups[ymd])
 585     elif mdy is not None:
 586         m, d, y = re.split(r'[-/\s]', groups[mdy])
 587     elif dmy is not None:
 588         d, m, y = re.split(r'[-/\s]', groups[dmy])
 589     elif d_m_y is not None:
 590         d, m, y = d_m_y
 591         d = groups[d]
 592         m = groups[m]
 593         y = groups[y]
 594     else:
 595         time_only = True
 596 
 597     H = M = S = u = 0
 598     if hms is not None and groups[hms]:
 599         t = groups[hms].split(':')
 600         if len(t) == 2:
 601             H, M = t
 602         else:
 603             H, M, S = t
 604             if '.' in S:
 605                 S, u = S.split('.')
 606                 u = int(float('.' + u) * 1000000)
 607             S = int(S)
 608         H = int(H)
 609         M = int(M)
 610 
 611     if am is not None:
 612         am = groups[am]
 613         if am:
 614             am = am.strip()
 615         if am == 'AM' and H == 12:
 616             # correction for "12" hour functioning as "0" hour: 12:15 AM = 00:15 by 24 hr clock
 617             H -= 12
 618         elif am == 'PM' and H == 12:
 619             # no correction needed: 12PM is midday, 12:00 by 24 hour clock
 620             pass
 621         elif am == 'PM':
 622             H += 12
 623 
 624     if tz is not None:
 625         tz = groups[tz]
 626     if tz == 'Z':
 627         tz = FixedTzOffset(0, 'UTC')
 628     elif tz:
 629         tz = tz.strip()
 630         if tz.isupper():
 631             # TODO use the awesome python TZ module?
 632             pass
 633         else:
 634             sign = tz[0]
 635             if ':' in tz:
 636                 tzh, tzm = tz[1:].split(':')
 637             elif len(tz) == 4:  # 'snnn'
 638                 tzh, tzm = tz[1], tz[2:4]
 639             else:
 640                 tzh, tzm = tz[1:3], tz[3:5]
 641             offset = int(tzm) + int(tzh) * 60
 642             if sign == '-':
 643                 offset = -offset
 644             tz = FixedTzOffset(offset, tz)
 645 
 646     if time_only:
 647         d = time(H, M, S, u, tzinfo=tz)
 648     else:
 649         y = int(y)
 650         if m.isdigit():
 651             m = int(m)
 652         else:
 653             m = MONTHS_MAP[m]
 654         d = int(d)
 655         d = datetime(y, m, d, H, M, S, u, tzinfo=tz)
 656 
 657     return d
 658 
 659 
 660 class TooManyFields(ValueError):
 661     pass
 662 
 663 
 664 class RepeatedNameError(ValueError):
 665     pass
 666 
 667 
 668 # note: {} are handled separately
 669 # note: I don't use r'' here because Sublime Text 2 syntax highlight has a fit
 670 REGEX_SAFETY = re.compile(r'([?\\\\.[\]()*+\^$!\|])')
 671 
 672 # allowed field types
 673 ALLOWED_TYPES = set(list('nbox%fFegwWdDsSl') +
 674     ['t' + c for c in 'ieahgcts'])
 675 
 676 
 677 def extract_format(format, extra_types):
 678     '''Pull apart the format [[fill]align][0][width][.precision][type]
 679     '''
 680     fill = align = None
 681     if format[0] in '<>=^':
 682         align = format[0]
 683         format = format[1:]
 684     elif len(format) > 1 and format[1] in '<>=^':
 685         fill = format[0]
 686         align = format[1]
 687         format = format[2:]
 688 
 689     zero = False
 690     if format and format[0] == '0':
 691         zero = True
 692         format = format[1:]
 693 
 694     width = ''
 695     while format:
 696         if not format[0].isdigit():
 697             break
 698         width += format[0]
 699         format = format[1:]
 700 
 701     if format.startswith('.'):
 702         # Precision isn't needed but we need to capture it so that
 703         # the ValueError isn't raised.
 704         format = format[1:]  # drop the '.'
 705         precision = ''
 706         while format:
 707             if not format[0].isdigit():
 708                 break
 709             precision += format[0]
 710             format = format[1:]
 711 
 712     # the rest is the type, if present
 713     type = format
 714     if type and type not in ALLOWED_TYPES and type not in extra_types:
 715         raise ValueError('format spec %r not recognised' % type)
 716 
 717     return locals()
 718 
 719 
 720 PARSE_RE = re.compile(r"""({{|}}|{\w*(?:(?:\.\w+)|(?:\[[^\]]+\]))*(?::[^}]+)?})""")
 721 
 722 
 723 class Parser(object):
 724     '''Encapsulate a format string that may be used to parse other strings.
 725     '''
 726     def __init__(self, format, extra_types=None, case_sensitive=False):
 727         # a mapping of a name as in {hello.world} to a regex-group compatible
 728         # name, like hello__world Its used to prevent the transformation of
 729         # name-to-group and group to name to fail subtly, such as in:
 730         # hello_.world-> hello___world->hello._world
 731         self._group_to_name_map = {}
 732         # also store the original field name to group name mapping to allow
 733         # multiple instances of a name in the format string
 734         self._name_to_group_map = {}
 735         # and to sanity check the repeated instances store away the first
 736         # field type specification for the named field
 737         self._name_types = {}
 738 
 739         self._format = format
 740         if extra_types is None:
 741             extra_types = {}
 742         self._extra_types = extra_types
 743         if case_sensitive:
 744             self._re_flags = re.DOTALL
 745         else:
 746             self._re_flags = re.IGNORECASE | re.DOTALL
 747         self._fixed_fields = []
 748         self._named_fields = []
 749         self._group_index = 0
 750         self._type_conversions = {}
 751         self._expression = self._generate_expression()
 752         self.__search_re = None
 753         self.__match_re = None
 754 
 755         log.debug('format %r -> %r', format, self._expression)
 756 
 757     def __repr__(self):
 758         if len(self._format) > 20:
 759             return '<%s %r>' % (self.__class__.__name__,
 760                 self._format[:17] + '...')
 761         return '<%s %r>' % (self.__class__.__name__, self._format)
 762 
 763     @property
 764     def _search_re(self):
 765         if self.__search_re is None:
 766             try:
 767                 self.__search_re = re.compile(self._expression, self._re_flags)
 768             except AssertionError:
 769                 # access error through sys to keep py3k and backward compat
 770                 e = str(sys.exc_info()[1])
 771                 if e.endswith('this version only supports 100 named groups'):
 772                     raise TooManyFields('sorry, you are attempting to parse '
 773                         'too many complex fields')
 774         return self.__search_re
 775 
 776     @property
 777     def _match_re(self):
 778         if self.__match_re is None:
 779             expression = r'^%s$' % self._expression
 780             try:
 781                 self.__match_re = re.compile(expression, self._re_flags)
 782             except AssertionError:
 783                 # access error through sys to keep py3k and backward compat
 784                 e = str(sys.exc_info()[1])
 785                 if e.endswith('this version only supports 100 named groups'):
 786                     raise TooManyFields('sorry, you are attempting to parse '
 787                         'too many complex fields')
 788             except re.error:
 789                 raise NotImplementedError("Group names (e.g. (?P<name>) can "
 790                     "cause failure, as they are not escaped properly: '%s'" %
 791                     expression)
 792         return self.__match_re
 793 
 794     def parse(self, string, evaluate_result=True):
 795         '''Match my format to the string exactly.
 796 
 797         Return a Result or Match instance or None if there's no match.
 798         '''
 799         m = self._match_re.match(string)
 800         if m is None:
 801             return None
 802 
 803         if evaluate_result:
 804             return self.evaluate_result(m)
 805         else:
 806             return Match(self, m)
 807 
 808     def search(self, string, pos=0, endpos=None, evaluate_result=True):
 809         '''Search the string for my format.
 810 
 811         Optionally start the search at "pos" character index and limit the
 812         search to a maximum index of endpos - equivalent to
 813         search(string[:endpos]).
 814 
 815         If the ``evaluate_result`` argument is set to ``False`` a
 816         Match instance is returned instead of the actual Result instance.
 817 
 818         Return either a Result instance or None if there's no match.
 819         '''
 820         if endpos is None:
 821             endpos = len(string)
 822         m = self._search_re.search(string, pos, endpos)
 823         if m is None:
 824             return None
 825 
 826         if evaluate_result:
 827             return self.evaluate_result(m)
 828         else:
 829             return Match(self, m)
 830 
 831     def findall(self, string, pos=0, endpos=None, extra_types=None, evaluate_result=True):
 832         '''Search "string" for all occurrences of "format".
 833 
 834         Optionally start the search at "pos" character index and limit the
 835         search to a maximum index of endpos - equivalent to
 836         search(string[:endpos]).
 837 
 838         Returns an iterator that holds Result or Match instances for each format match
 839         found.
 840         '''
 841         if endpos is None:
 842             endpos = len(string)
 843         return ResultIterator(self, string, pos, endpos, evaluate_result=evaluate_result)
 844 
 845     def _expand_named_fields(self, named_fields):
 846         result = {}
 847         for field, value in named_fields.items():
 848             # split 'aaa[bbb][ccc]...' into 'aaa' and '[bbb][ccc]...'
 849             basename, subkeys = re.match(r'([^\[]+)(.*)', field).groups()
 850 
 851             # create nested dictionaries {'aaa': {'bbb': {'ccc': ...}}}
 852             d = result
 853             k = basename
 854 
 855             if subkeys:
 856                 for subkey in re.findall(r'\[[^\]]+\]', subkeys):
 857                     d = d.setdefault(k,{})
 858                     k = subkey[1:-1]
 859 
 860             # assign the value to the last key
 861             d[k] = value
 862 
 863         return result
 864 
 865     def evaluate_result(self, m):
 866         '''Generate a Result instance for the given regex match object'''
 867         # ok, figure the fixed fields we've pulled out and type convert them
 868         fixed_fields = list(m.groups())
 869         for n in self._fixed_fields:
 870             if n in self._type_conversions:
 871                 fixed_fields[n] = self._type_conversions[n](fixed_fields[n], m)
 872         fixed_fields = tuple(fixed_fields[n] for n in self._fixed_fields)
 873 
 874         # grab the named fields, converting where requested
 875         groupdict = m.groupdict()
 876         named_fields = {}
 877         name_map = {}
 878         for k in self._named_fields:
 879             korig = self._group_to_name_map[k]
 880             name_map[korig] = k
 881             if k in self._type_conversions:
 882                 value = self._type_conversions[k](groupdict[k], m)
 883             else:
 884                 value = groupdict[k]
 885 
 886             named_fields[korig] = value
 887 
 888         # now figure the match spans
 889         spans = dict((n, m.span(name_map[n])) for n in named_fields)
 890         spans.update((i, m.span(n + 1))
 891             for i, n in enumerate(self._fixed_fields))
 892 
 893         # and that's our result
 894         return Result(fixed_fields, self._expand_named_fields(named_fields), spans)
 895 
 896     def _regex_replace(self, match):
 897         return '\\' + match.group(1)
 898 
 899     def _generate_expression(self):
 900         # turn my _format attribute into the _expression attribute
 901         e = []
 902         for part in PARSE_RE.split(self._format):
 903             if not part:
 904                 continue
 905             elif part == '{{':
 906                 e.append(r'\{')
 907             elif part == '}}':
 908                 e.append(r'\}')
 909             elif part[0] == '{' and part[-1] == '}':
 910                 # this will be a braces-delimited field to handle
 911                 e.append(self._handle_field(part))
 912             else:
 913                 # just some text to match
 914                 e.append(REGEX_SAFETY.sub(self._regex_replace, part))
 915         return ''.join(e)
 916 
 917     def _to_group_name(self, field):
 918         # return a version of field which can be used as capture group, even
 919         # though it might contain '.'
 920         group = field.replace('.', '_').replace('[', '_').replace(']', '_')
 921 
 922         # make sure we don't collide ("a.b" colliding with "a_b")
 923         n = 1
 924         while group in self._group_to_name_map:
 925             n += 1
 926             if '.' in field:
 927                 group = field.replace('.', '_' * n)
 928             elif '_' in field:
 929                 group = field.replace('_', '_' * n)
 930             else:
 931                 raise KeyError('duplicated group name %r' % (field,))
 932 
 933         # save off the mapping
 934         self._group_to_name_map[group] = field
 935         self._name_to_group_map[field] = group
 936         return group
 937 
 938     def _handle_field(self, field):
 939         # first: lose the braces
 940         field = field[1:-1]
 941 
 942         # now figure whether this is an anonymous or named field, and whether
 943         # there's any format specification
 944         format = ''
 945         if field and field[0].isalpha():
 946             if ':' in field:
 947                 name, format = field.split(':')
 948             else:
 949                 name = field
 950             if name in self._name_to_group_map:
 951                 if self._name_types[name] != format:
 952                     raise RepeatedNameError('field type %r for field "%s" '
 953                         'does not match previous seen type %r' % (format,
 954                         name, self._name_types[name]))
 955                 group = self._name_to_group_map[name]
 956                 # match previously-seen value
 957                 return r'(?P=%s)' % group
 958             else:
 959                 group = self._to_group_name(name)
 960                 self._name_types[name] = format
 961             self._named_fields.append(group)
 962             # this will become a group, which must not contain dots
 963             wrap = r'(?P<%s>%%s)' % group
 964         else:
 965             self._fixed_fields.append(self._group_index)
 966             wrap = r'(%s)'
 967             if ':' in field:
 968                 format = field[1:]
 969             group = self._group_index
 970 
 971         # simplest case: no type specifier ({} or {name})
 972         if not format:
 973             self._group_index += 1
 974             return wrap % r'.+?'
 975 
 976         # decode the format specification
 977         format = extract_format(format, self._extra_types)
 978 
 979         # figure type conversions, if any
 980         type = format['type']
 981         is_numeric = type and type in 'n%fegdobx'
 982         if type in self._extra_types:
 983             type_converter = self._extra_types[type]
 984             s = getattr(type_converter, 'pattern', r'.+?')
 985             regex_group_count = getattr(type_converter, 'regex_group_count', 0)
 986             if regex_group_count is None:
 987                 regex_group_count = 0
 988             self._group_index += regex_group_count
 989 
 990             def f(string, m):
 991                 return type_converter(string)
 992             self._type_conversions[group] = f
 993         elif type == 'n':
 994             s = r'\d{1,3}([,.]\d{3})*'
 995             self._group_index += 1
 996             self._type_conversions[group] = int_convert(10)
 997         elif type == 'b':
 998             s = r'(0[bB])?[01]+'
 999             self._type_conversions[group] = int_convert(2)
1000             self._group_index += 1
1001         elif type == 'o':
1002             s = r'(0[oO])?[0-7]+'
1003             self._type_conversions[group] = int_convert(8)
1004             self._group_index += 1
1005         elif type == 'x':
1006             s = r'(0[xX])?[0-9a-fA-F]+'
1007             self._type_conversions[group] = int_convert(16)
1008             self._group_index += 1
1009         elif type == '%':
1010             s = r'\d+(\.\d+)?%'
1011             self._group_index += 1
1012             self._type_conversions[group] = percentage
1013         elif type == 'f':
1014             s = r'\d*\.\d+'
1015             self._type_conversions[group] = lambda s, m: float(s)
1016         elif type == 'F':
1017             s = r'\d*\.\d+'
1018             self._type_conversions[group] = lambda s, m: Decimal(s)
1019         elif type == 'e':
1020             s = r'\d*\.\d+[eE][-+]?\d+|nan|NAN|[-+]?inf|[-+]?INF'
1021             self._type_conversions[group] = lambda s, m: float(s)
1022         elif type == 'g':
1023             s = r'\d+(\.\d+)?([eE][-+]?\d+)?|nan|NAN|[-+]?inf|[-+]?INF'
1024             self._group_index += 2
1025             self._type_conversions[group] = lambda s, m: float(s)
1026         elif type == 'd':
1027             if format.get('width'):
1028                 width = r'{1,%s}' % int(format['width'])
1029             else:
1030                 width = '+'
1031             s = r'\d{w}|[-+ ]?0[xX][0-9a-fA-F]{w}|[-+ ]?0[bB][01]{w}|[-+ ]?0[oO][0-7]{w}'.format(w=width)
1032             self._type_conversions[group] = int_convert() # do not specify numeber base, determine it automatically
1033         elif type == 'ti':
1034             s = r'(\d{4}-\d\d-\d\d)((\s+|T)%s)?(Z|\s*[-+]\d\d:?\d\d)?' % \
1035                 TIME_PAT
1036             n = self._group_index
1037             self._type_conversions[group] = partial(date_convert, ymd=n + 1,
1038                 hms=n + 4, tz=n + 7)
1039             self._group_index += 7
1040         elif type == 'tg':
1041             s = r'(\d{1,2}[-/](\d{1,2}|%s)[-/]\d{4})(\s+%s)?%s?%s?' % (
1042                 ALL_MONTHS_PAT, TIME_PAT, AM_PAT, TZ_PAT)
1043             n = self._group_index
1044             self._type_conversions[group] = partial(date_convert, dmy=n + 1,
1045                 hms=n + 5, am=n + 8, tz=n + 9)
1046             self._group_index += 9
1047         elif type == 'ta':
1048             s = r'((\d{1,2}|%s)[-/]\d{1,2}[-/]\d{4})(\s+%s)?%s?%s?' % (
1049                 ALL_MONTHS_PAT, TIME_PAT, AM_PAT, TZ_PAT)
1050             n = self._group_index
1051             self._type_conversions[group] = partial(date_convert, mdy=n + 1,
1052                 hms=n + 5, am=n + 8, tz=n + 9)
1053             self._group_index += 9
1054         elif type == 'te':
1055             # this will allow microseconds through if they're present, but meh
1056             s = r'(%s,\s+)?(\d{1,2}\s+%s\s+\d{4})\s+%s%s' % (DAYS_PAT,
1057                 MONTHS_PAT, TIME_PAT, TZ_PAT)
1058             n = self._group_index
1059             self._type_conversions[group] = partial(date_convert, dmy=n + 3,
1060                 hms=n + 5, tz=n + 8)
1061             self._group_index += 8
1062         elif type == 'th':
1063             # slight flexibility here from the stock Apache format
1064             s = r'(\d{1,2}[-/]%s[-/]\d{4}):%s%s' % (MONTHS_PAT, TIME_PAT,
1065                 TZ_PAT)
1066             n = self._group_index
1067             self._type_conversions[group] = partial(date_convert, dmy=n + 1,
1068                 hms=n + 3, tz=n + 6)
1069             self._group_index += 6
1070         elif type == 'tc':
1071             s = r'(%s)\s+%s\s+(\d{1,2})\s+%s\s+(\d{4})' % (
1072                 DAYS_PAT, MONTHS_PAT, TIME_PAT)
1073             n = self._group_index
1074             self._type_conversions[group] = partial(date_convert,
1075                 d_m_y=(n + 4, n + 3, n + 8), hms=n + 5)
1076             self._group_index += 8
1077         elif type == 'tt':
1078             s = r'%s?%s?%s?' % (TIME_PAT, AM_PAT, TZ_PAT)
1079             n = self._group_index
1080             self._type_conversions[group] = partial(date_convert, hms=n + 1,
1081                 am=n + 4, tz=n + 5)
1082             self._group_index += 5
1083         elif type == 'ts':
1084             s = r'%s(\s+)(\d+)(\s+)(\d{1,2}:\d{1,2}:\d{1,2})?' % MONTHS_PAT
1085             n = self._group_index
1086             self._type_conversions[group] = partial(date_convert, mm=n+1, dd=n+3,
1087                 hms=n + 5)
1088             self._group_index += 5
1089         elif type == 'l':
1090             s = r'[A-Za-z]+'
1091         elif type:
1092             s = r'\%s+' % type
1093         elif format.get('precision'):
1094             if format.get('width'):
1095                 s = r'.{%s,%s}?' % (format['width'], format['precision'])
1096             else:
1097                 s = r'.{1,%s}?' % format['precision']
1098         elif format.get('width'):
1099             s = r'.{%s,}?' % format['width']
1100         else:
1101             s = r'.+?'
1102 
1103         align = format['align']
1104         fill = format['fill']
1105 
1106         # handle some numeric-specific things like fill and sign
1107         if is_numeric:
1108             # prefix with something (align "=" trumps zero)
1109             if align == '=':
1110                 # special case - align "=" acts like the zero above but with
1111                 # configurable fill defaulting to "0"
1112                 if not fill:
1113                     fill = '0'
1114                 s = r'%s*' % fill + s
1115 
1116             # allow numbers to be prefixed with a sign
1117             s = r'[-+ ]?' + s
1118 
1119         if not fill:
1120             fill = ' '
1121 
1122         # Place into a group now - this captures the value we want to keep.
1123         # Everything else from now is just padding to be stripped off
1124         if wrap:
1125             s = wrap % s
1126             self._group_index += 1
1127 
1128         if format['width']:
1129             # all we really care about is that if the format originally
1130             # specified a width then there will probably be padding - without
1131             # an explicit alignment that'll mean right alignment with spaces
1132             # padding
1133             if not align:
1134                 align = '>'
1135 
1136         if fill in r'.\+?*[](){}^$':
1137             fill = '\\' + fill
1138 
1139         # align "=" has been handled
1140         if align == '<':
1141             s = '%s%s*' % (s, fill)
1142         elif align == '>':
1143             s = '%s*%s' % (fill, s)
1144         elif align == '^':
1145             s = '%s*%s%s*' % (fill, s, fill)
1146 
1147         return s
1148 
1149 
1150 class Result(object):
1151     '''The result of a parse() or search().
1152 
1153     Fixed results may be looked up using `result[index]`.
1154 
1155     Named results may be looked up using `result['name']`.
1156 
1157     Named results may be tested for existence using `'name' in result`.
1158     '''
1159     def __init__(self, fixed, named, spans):
1160         self.fixed = fixed
1161         self.named = named
1162         self.spans = spans
1163 
1164     def __getitem__(self, item):
1165         if isinstance(item, int):
1166             return self.fixed[item]
1167         return self.named[item]
1168 
1169     def __repr__(self):
1170         return '<%s %r %r>' % (self.__class__.__name__, self.fixed,
1171             self.named)
1172 
1173     def __contains__(self, name):
1174         return name in self.named
1175 
1176 
1177 class Match(object):
1178     '''The result of a parse() or search() if no results are generated.
1179 
1180     This class is only used to expose internal used regex match objects
1181     to the user and use them for external Parser.evaluate_result calls.
1182     '''
1183     def __init__(self, parser, match):
1184         self.parser = parser
1185         self.match = match
1186 
1187     def evaluate_result(self):
1188         '''Generate results for this Match'''
1189         return self.parser.evaluate_result(self.match)

1191 
1192 class ResultIterator(object):
1193     '''The result of a findall() operation.
1194 
1195     Each element is a Result instance.
1196     '''
1197     def __init__(self, parser, string, pos, endpos, evaluate_result=True):
1198         self.parser = parser
1199         self.string = string
1200         self.pos = pos
1201         self.endpos = endpos
1202         self.evaluate_result = evaluate_result
1203 
1204     def __iter__(self):
1205         return self
1206 
1207     def __next__(self):
1208         m = self.parser._search_re.search(self.string, self.pos, self.endpos)
1209         if m is None:
1210             raise StopIteration()
1211         self.pos = m.end()
1212 
1213         if self.evaluate_result:
1214             return self.parser.evaluate_result(m)
1215         else:
1216             return Match(self.parser, m)
1217 
1218     # pre-py3k compat
1219     next = __next__
1220

1222 def parse(format, string, extra_types=None, evaluate_result=True, case_sensitive=False):
1223     '''Using "format" attempt to pull values from "string".
1224 
1225     The format must match the string contents exactly. If the value
1226     you're looking for is instead just a part of the string use
1227     search().
1228 
1229     If ``evaluate_result`` is True the return value will be an Result instance with two attributes:
1230 
1231      .fixed - tuple of fixed-position values from the string
1232      .named - dict of named values from the string
1233 
1234     If ``evaluate_result`` is False the return value will be a Match instance with one method:
1235 
1236      .evaluate_result() - This will return a Result instance like you would get
1237                           with ``evaluate_result`` set to True
1238 
1239     The default behaviour is to match strings case insensitively. You may match with
1240     case by specifying case_sensitive=True.
1241 
1242     If the format is invalid a ValueError will be raised.
1243 
1244     See the module documentation for the use of "extra_types".
1245 
1246     In the case there is no match parse() will return None.
1247     '''
1248     p = Parser(format, extra_types=extra_types, case_sensitive=case_sensitive)
1249     return p.parse(string, evaluate_result=evaluate_result)

1252 def search(format, string, pos=0, endpos=None, extra_types=None, evaluate_result=True,
1253         case_sensitive=False):
1254     '''Search "string" for the first occurrence of "format".
1255 
1256     The format may occur anywhere within the string. If
1257     instead you wish for the format to exactly match the string
1258     use parse().
1259 
1260     Optionally start the search at "pos" character index and limit the search
1261     to a maximum index of endpos - equivalent to search(string[:endpos]).
1262 
1263     If ``evaluate_result`` is True the return value will be an Result instance with two attributes:
1264 
1265      .fixed - tuple of fixed-position values from the string
1266      .named - dict of named values from the string
1267 
1268     If ``evaluate_result`` is False the return value will be a Match instance with one method:
1269 
1270      .evaluate_result() - This will return a Result instance like you would get
1271                           with ``evaluate_result`` set to True
1272 
1273     The default behaviour is to match strings case insensitively. You may match with
1274     case by specifying case_sensitive=True.
1275 
1276     If the format is invalid a ValueError will be raised.
1277 
1278     See the module documentation for the use of "extra_types".
1279 
1280     In the case there is no match parse() will return None.
1281     '''
1282     p = Parser(format, extra_types=extra_types, case_sensitive=case_sensitive)
1283     return p.search(string, pos, endpos, evaluate_result=evaluate_result)

1286 def findall(format, string, pos=0, endpos=None, extra_types=None, evaluate_result=True,
1287         case_sensitive=False):
1288     '''Search "string" for all occurrences of "format".
1289 
1290     You will be returned an iterator that holds Result instances
1291     for each format match found.
1292 
1293     Optionally start the search at "pos" character index and limit the search
1294     to a maximum index of endpos - equivalent to search(string[:endpos]).
1295 
1296     If ``evaluate_result`` is True each returned Result instance has two attributes:
1297 
1298      .fixed - tuple of fixed-position values from the string
1299      .named - dict of named values from the string
1300 
1301     If ``evaluate_result`` is False each returned value is a Match instance with one method:
1302 
1303      .evaluate_result() - This will return a Result instance like you would get
1304                           with ``evaluate_result`` set to True
1305 
1306     The default behaviour is to match strings case insensitively. You may match with
1307     case by specifying case_sensitive=True.
1308 
1309     If the format is invalid a ValueError will be raised.
1310 
1311     See the module documentation for the use of "extra_types".
1312     '''
1313     p = Parser(format, extra_types=extra_types, case_sensitive=case_sensitive)
1314     return Parser(format, extra_types=extra_types).findall(string, pos, endpos, evaluate_result=evaluate_result)

1317 def compile(format, extra_types=None, case_sensitive=False):
1318     '''Create a Parser instance to parse "format".
1319 
1320     The resultant Parser has a method .parse(string) which
1321     behaves in the same manner as parse(format, string).
1322 
1323     The default behaviour is to match strings case insensitively. You may match with
1324     case by specifying case_sensitive=True.
1325 
1326     Use this function if you intend to parse many strings
1327     with the same format.
1328 
1329     See the module documentation for the use of "extra_types".
1330 
1331     Returns a Parser instance.
1332     '''
1333     return Parser(format, extra_types=extra_types, case_sensitive=case_sensitive)
